                <div type="textpart" subtype="text" n="a">
                    <ab><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>ιεναι</orig></ab>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" subtype="text" n="b">
                    <ab><orig>ορμαθ</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></ab>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" subtype="text" n="c">
                    <ab><orig>ικω<unclear>ο</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></ab>
                </div>
                </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Intraduisible.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Gasperini gave no interpretation of this item. C. Dobias-Lalou adds the following observations: 1) The fragmentary words might belong to a trade mark, for 
                    there might be in b) a form of the verb <foreign xml:lang="grc">ὁρμάω</foreign>. 2) The tall hasta at the beginning of c might be a separator rather than an 
                    iota. If so, the name of the island and city of Cos would be a possibility. 3) The first letter of a) is perhaps no iota, but rather part of another letter.
                    Without autopsy it would be hazardous to guess more.
                    
                </p>
            </div></body>
